---
description: C# code style, naming conventions, and project structure for YuckQi
globs: **/*.cs,**/Directory.Packages.props
alwaysApply: true
---

When creating or editing `.cs` files, apply every section below. Do not rely on memory—treat this file as the source of truth.

# Code Style

- Use file-scoped namespaces (`namespace X;`)
- Type definitions (class, struct, interface, record) that have no body should be terminated with a semicolon (e.g., `class Foo;` not `class Foo { }`)
- Use primary constructors for dependency injection and parameter forwarding
- Use full CLR type names: `String`, `Boolean`, `Int32`, `Object` (not `string`, `bool`, `int`, `object`)
- Use `var` for local variables
- Use `ArgumentNullException.ThrowIfNull()` for null guards
- Use `is null` for null checks and `is not null` for non-null checks (not `== null` or `!= null`)
- Use block bodies for methods even when single-expression; expression-bodied properties are acceptable
- Place a space before the `!` negation operator (e.g., `! String.IsNullOrWhiteSpace(value)`)
- Omit braces for single-statement `if` blocks
- Mark concrete exception classes as `sealed`
- Use `CancellationToken.None` instead of `default` when a `CancellationToken` value is needed; the explicit form communicates intent more clearly
- Do not add code comments unless they explain non-obvious intent
- Do not wrap long lines
- In chained method calls, align continuation `.` with the `.` on the first line (e.g., indent so all `.` share the same column)
- Files should be named to match the class they contain
- Alphabetize `using` statements with all `System` namespaces listed first
- Never use fully-qualified attribute names; import the namespace with a `using` statement and use the short form (e.g., `[Key]` not `[System.ComponentModel.DataAnnotations.Key]`)
- Place a blank line after a set of variable declarations before other statements
- Place a blank line before `return` statements (when preceded by other statements)
- Place a space after the closing parenthesis of a type cast (e.g., `(Int16) 7` not `(Int16)7`)
- Use local functions instead of lambda expressions when possible
- Local functions should appear after a `return;` statement at the end of the method body
- Properties should be separated by a single blank line
- Properties should be listed in alphabetical order in the class which defines them

# Naming Conventions

- Private fields: `_camelCase` (underscore prefix)
- Public members, properties, methods: `PascalCase`
- Descriptive generic type parameters: `TDomainEntity`, `TIdentifier`, `TScope`, `TRecord`, `TData`
- Interfaces: `I` prefix (e.g. `ICreationHandler`)
- Abstract base classes: `Base` suffix (e.g. `CreationHandlerBase`)
- Protected abstract methods: `Do` prefix (e.g. `DoCreate`, `DoGet`, `DoRevise`)
- Extension method classes: `*Extensions` suffix (e.g. `FilterCriteriaExtensions`, `DynamicParameterExtensions`)
- Avoid using abbreviations when naming variables (e.g., prefer `connection` instead of `conn`, `dictionary` instead of `dict`); exception: `unitOfWork` should be abbreviated to `uow`
- Lambda expression parameters: use `t` as the default temporary variable name regardless of the underlying type; when there are conflicts (e.g. nested lambdas), use `u`, `v`, etc. in sequence (e.g., `t => parameters.Any(u => u.Name == t)`)
- Unit test method names use `MethodName_Condition_ExpectedResult` format (e.g. `Delete_WhenNotDeleted_SetsDeletionMoment`)
- Mock variables: do not prefix with `mock`; name them after what they represent (e.g., `scope` not `mockScope`, `cursor` not `mockCursor`)

# Design Patterns

- **Template Method**: Base classes define public workflow; subclasses override `DoXxx` abstract methods
- **Convenience overloads**: Provide a simpler generic signature (fewer type params) that defaults `TData` to `TDomainEntity` via primary constructor forwarding
- **Sync + Async parity**: Every operation has both synchronous and `Task`-returning async overloads (async overloads accept `CancellationToken`)
- **Scope pattern**: Operations accept a `TScope?` parameter representing the data store context (e.g. `IDbTransaction`)
- **Composition**: Handlers that delegate to other handlers (e.g. `ActivationHandler`, `LogicalDeletionHandler`) implement their interface directly without a base class
- **Optional mapper**: `IMapper?` enables mapping between domain entities and data records; when null, identity mapping is assumed

# Project Structure

- `src/` for source projects, `test/` for test projects
- Core abstractions live in `YuckQi.Data`; provider implementations in provider-specific projects (e.g. `YuckQi.Data.Sql.Dapper`, `YuckQi.Data.DocumentDb.MongoDb`)
- Organize by concern: `Handlers/Read/`, `Handlers/Write/`, `Exceptions/`, `Filtering/`, `Sorting/`
- Place base classes in an `Abstract/` subfolder; interfaces in `Abstract/Interfaces/`
- Test projects mirror source names with a `.UnitTests` suffix; use NUnit

# Versioning

NuGet package version is defined in `src/Directory.Build.props` as `<Version>`. When updating the version:

- **Major**: Matches the .NET SDK version targeted (e.g. `8` for `net8.0`). Change when upgrading the target framework.
- **Minor**: Increment only when there are **breaking changes** (removed or changed public API, changed behavior that breaks existing callers).
- **Revision** (third segment): Increment for all other releases—new features, bug fixes, refactors, and any non-breaking changes.

Example: after adding new caching behaviors with no breaking changes, bump the revision (e.g. `8.3.1` → `8.3.2`).

# NuGet / Dependencies

- **MediatR**: Use only a 12.x version (e.g. `12.5.0`). Do **not** upgrade to MediatR 13.x or 14.x; those lines require a paid license. Pin the version in `Directory.Packages.props` and keep it within the 12.x range when updating.
